            <h1 class="page-heading">From Plato to behind the plate</h1>

            <h2 class="page-subheadline">UCI philosophy grad and baseball star Francis Larson leaves prestigious London school to reconnect with his first love - baseball.</h2>

            <div class="page-date">
                
	by Tom Vasich, University Communications | 

                May 31, 2011            </div>

            
            <div class="page-content clearfix"><p>In the storied history of UC Irvine baseball, no one has hit more home runs than Francis Larson. Yet when the <a href="http://www.ucirvinesports.com/sports/m-basebl/mtt/larson_francis00.html" target="_blank">record-setting catcher </a>graduated in 2010 with an offer to play in the Angels‚Äô minor league system, he did what might be expected from a philosophy student: turned his back on convention.</p>
<p>Larson chose instead to matriculate at the prestigious London School of Economics &amp; Political Science, diving headfirst into one of the most challenging academic environments in the world. But as the damp, chilly English winter turned to spring, his baseball dreams revived. And the Angels‚Äô offer still stood.</p>
<p>So in April, Larson ‚Äî a Yorba Linda native and 2010 UCI Scholar-Athlete of the Year ‚Äî signed with his hometown team and reported to extended spring training at its Tempe, Ariz., facility. He hasn‚Äôt turned his back on LSE, as the school is called, and is finishing up the spring term in his spare time.</p>
<p><strong>Q: What‚Äôs it like to play professional baseball while still taking classes?</strong></p>
<p><strong>A:</strong> Since I signed, life‚Äôs been a little hectic. I‚Äôve been working out all day and then studying at night, meeting about 60 new faces, and readjusting to life as an athlete. I never realized how hard it is to study something when you‚Äôre 6,000 miles away from the classes. The distance makes it seem extra esoteric. I‚Äôm enjoying it, though. And Starbucks is enjoying my business.</p>
<p><strong>Q: During your senior year at UCI, you were drafted in the 22nd round by the Angels but went to LSE instead. Why?</strong></p>
<p><strong>A:</strong> The short answer is that I needed perspective. I‚Äôd spent the bulk of my life in Orange County. I grew up in Yorba Linda, went to high school in Anaheim and then college in Irvine. These are all wonderful places ‚Äî I mean, Yorba Linda is called ‚Äúthe land of gracious living‚Äù ‚Äî but I needed to see something other than a Southern California suburb.</p>
<p>Also, I‚Äôd spent virtually all my free time since I was about 6 years old playing baseball. Now don‚Äôt get me wrong: I love baseball. It stretches beyond strikes and runs. I just love being on a team, winning on a team. But when you‚Äôve never not been on a team, you start to wonder what life‚Äôs like out there.</p>
<p>Additionally, I‚Äôd been good at school since I was a little boy; I always liked to learn. When I played baseball, though, I couldn‚Äôt spend lots of hours on academia. So while I did well in college course work, I thought to myself, ‚ÄúWhat if I devoted myself full time to this sort of stuff? Who knows what could happen.‚Äù</p>
<p>After being drafted, I had some major questions to answer. I didn‚Äôt want to go into pro baseball and always be wondering what life would‚Äôve been like if I had pursued working with my mind. If I was going to commit to something, I wanted it to be a full commitment.</p>
<p><strong>Q: How was your experience at LSE? What did you study?</strong></p>
<p><strong>A:</strong> It was mind-blowing ‚Äî and that‚Äôs not hyperbole! I moved to London in August, with no apartment and no idea what life in a big city was like. But once I got the hang of living in ultra-central London, I started to really enjoy it. There‚Äôs so much energy there. Every day, I was riding the Tube, with everyone dressed in nice suits, reading the Financial Times. You can feel the pulse of business and the financial markets there. That‚Äôs something I‚Äôll never forget.</p>
<p>When people hear I‚Äôm at LSE, they automatically think I‚Äôm studying economics. What I‚Äôm studying is closer to socioeconomic theory. My master‚Äôs program is in philosophy of the social sciences. To be honest, though, I learned the most outside class. Although the department‚Äôs the best in the world for this particular discipline, I learned more about the practical side of life than the theoretical.</p>
<p>And when I say ‚Äúpractical,‚Äù I mean things like the business world and the financial markets. LSE is on the edge of London‚Äôs financial district, and all the major investment banks recruit there. The students are in an investment banking hysteria; the vast majority of them are looking to enter finance. It‚Äôs truly a mania. When I investigated to see what all the fuss was about, I found out I absolutely love the financial realm. I met a lot of international students who want to take over the world. You don‚Äôt move to London to just get by; these people were intellectual go-getters.</p>
<p><strong>Q: Why did you choose to come back to baseball?</strong></p>
<p><strong>A:</strong> There was a point in London when I had seen what I wanted to see. I found out what it‚Äôs like to pursue academia full time, sit inside all day reading arcane theory, be around super-goal-oriented people. I saw how big-city business life operates, what it‚Äôs like to live in another culture. I learned what sort of industry I want to be involved with in the future and what it‚Äôs like not being on a team.</p>
<p>My conclusion from all this? There‚Äôs no better job on planet Earth than being paid to play a game. The idea that someone would give me money to play on a team, in the sun, in front of people, is just incomparable. If you go to work for Goldman Sachs, you won‚Äôt get that. You might get close, but it‚Äôs not like baseball. I found out where the grass is greenest: on a baseball field.</p>
<p><strong>Q: You might be the only professional baseball player with a degree in philosophy. How does this help you, especially as a catcher?</strong></p>
<p><strong>A:</strong> One of our pitching coaches here in Arizona is really into philosophy ‚Äî or what most people think is philosophy. He asked me whether I‚Äôd read <em>The Art of War</em>, and I told him that‚Äôs not what we read in philosophy.</p>
<p>But sure, it‚Äôs an asset to me as a baseball player. Once you‚Äôve dealt with the most fundamental, difficult ideas conceivable, you can sort of take things inside the lines in stride. Everything is simple. Baseball becomes a game about hitting a ball, not about ‚Äúdoubles‚Äù or ‚Äúruns.‚Äù You see life for what it is. Then it starts being fun.</p>
<p><strong>Q: What‚Äôs harder: understanding Immanuel Kant‚Äôs doctrine of transcendental idealism or hitting a curveball?</strong></p>
<p><strong>A:</strong> Here‚Äôs something telling: If you can understand Kant, you can get paid $60,000 a year to teach undergrads. If you can hit a curveball, well, you can potentially get paid millions.</p>
<p><strong>Q: What‚Äôs your plan for the next few years?</strong></p>
<p><strong>A:</strong> I used to think planners were the ones who win in life. They aren‚Äôt; it‚Äôs the opportunists. For now, I‚Äôm going to hit and catch baseballs.</p>
<p><strong>Q: Anything you want to say to your fans at UCI?</strong></p>
<p><strong>A:</strong> Thanks for all the support. The UCI fans did something really amazing: They wouldn‚Äôt just root for the brand, UCI. They‚Äôd root for the guys on the field. That was huge, and I enjoyed being on the receiving end of that.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>

